# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-compute-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] Google Cloud provides infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and serverless computing environments.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] In April 2008, Google announced App Engine, a platform for developing and hosting web applications in Google-managed data centers, which was the first cloud computing service from the company.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] The service became generally available in November 2011.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] Since the announcement of App Engine, Google added multiple cloud services to the platform.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] Google lists over 100 products under the Google Cloud brand.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] Some of the key services are listed below.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] A region is a specific geographical location where users can deploy cloud resources.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] Each region is an independent geographic area that consists of zones.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] A zone is a deployment area for Google Cloud Platform resources within a region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] Zones should be considered a single failure domain within a region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] As of Q1 2024, Google Cloud Platform is available in 40 regions and 121 zones.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] For those familiar with other notable cloud service providers, a comparison of similar services may be helpful in understanding Google Cloud Platform's offerings.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-cloud-platform] Customers announced in 2023 include Kingfisher plc, the Government of Kuwait, Deutsche Börse Group, Unity Technologies, Uber, FanCode, Daimler, and Wix.com.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google announced Compute Engine on June 28, 2012, at Google I/O 2012 in a limited preview mode.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] In April 2013, GCE was made available to customers with Gold Support Package.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] On February 25, 2013, Google announced that RightScale was their first reseller.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] During Google I/O 2013, many features including sub-hour billing, shared-core instance types, larger persistent disks, enhanced SDN based networking capabilities and ISO/IEC 27001 certification got announced.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] GCE became available to everyone on May 15, 2013.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Layer 3 load balancing came to GCE on August 7, 2013.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Finally, on December 2, 2013, Google announced that GCE is generally available.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] It also expanded the OS support, enabled live migration of VMs, 16-core instances, faster persistent disks and lowered the price of standard instances.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] At the Google Cloud Platform Live event on March 25, 2014, Urs Hölzle, Senior VP of technical infrastructure announced sustained usage discounts, support for Microsoft Windows Server 2008 R2, Cloud DNS and Cloud Deployment Manager.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] On May 28, 2014, Google announced optimizations for LXC containers along with dynamic scheduling of Docker containers across a fleet of VM instances.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google Compute Engine Unit (GCEU), which is pronounced as GQ, is an abstraction of computing resources.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] According to Google, 2.75 GCEUs represent the minimum power of one logical core (a hardware hyper-thread) based on the Sandy Bridge platform.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Voellm out of a need to compare the performance of virtual machines offered by Google.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] It is approximated by the Coremark(TM) benchmark run as part of the PerfKitBenchmarker Open Source benchmark created by Google in partnership with many Cloud Providers.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Every Google Compute Engine instance starts with a disk resource called persistent disk.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Persistent disk provides the disk space for instances and contains the root filesystem from which the instance boots.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Persistent disks can be used as raw block devices.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] By default, Google Compute Engine uses SCSI for attaching persistent disks.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Persistent Disks provide straightforward, consistent and reliable storage at a consistent and reliable price, removing the need for a separate local ephemeral disk.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Persistent disks need to be created before launching an instance.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Once attached to an instance, they can be formatted with the native filesystem.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A single persistent disk can be attached to multiple instances in read-only mode.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Each persistent disk can be up to 10 TB in size.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google Compute Engine encrypts the persistent disks with AES-128-CB, and this encryption is applied before the data leaves the virtual machine monitor and hits the disk.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Encryption is always enabled and is transparent to Google Compute Engine users.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] The integrity of persistent disks is maintained via a HMAC scheme.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] On June 18, 2014, Google announced support for SSD persistent disks.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] These disks deliver up to 30 IOPS per GB which is 20x more write IOPS and 100x more read IOPS than the standard persistent disks.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] An image is a persistent disk that contains the operating system and root file system that is necessary for starting an instance.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] An image must be selected while creating an instance or during the creation of a root persistent disk.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] By default, Google Compute Engine installs the root filesystem defined by the image on a root persistent disk.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google Compute Engine provides CentOS and Debian images as standard Linux images.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) and Microsoft Windows Server 2008 R2 images are a part of the premier operating system images which are available for an additional fee.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Container Linux (formerly CoreOS), the lightweight Linux OS based on ChromiumOS is also supported on Google Compute Engine.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google Compute Engine uses KVM as the hypervisor, and supports guest images running Linux and Microsoft Windows which are used to launch virtual machines based on the 64 bit x86 architecture.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] The prices mentioned below are based on running standard Debian or CentOS Linux virtual machines (VMs).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] VMs running proprietary operating systems will be charged more.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Compute Engine connects various entities called resources that will be a part of the deployment.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Each resource performs a different function.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] When a virtual machine instance is launched, an instance resource is created that uses other resources, such as disk resources, network resources and image resources.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] For example, a disk resource functions as data storage for the virtual machine, similar to a physical hard drive, and a network resource helps regulate traffic to and from the instances.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] An image resource contains an operating system and root file system necessary for starting the instance.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google maintains and provides images that are ready-to-use or users can customize an image and use that as an image of choice for creating instances.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Depending on the needs, users can also apply an image to a persistent disk and use the persistent disk as the root file system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] An instance's machine type determines the number of cores, the memory, and the I/O operations supported by the instance.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Persistent disks are independent of the virtual machines and outlive an instance's lifespan.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] All information stored on the persistent disks is encrypted before being written to physical media, and the keys are tightly controlled by Google.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Each instance can attach only a limited amount of total persistent disk space (one can have up to 64 TB on most instances) and a limited number of individual persistent disks (one can attach up to 16 independent persistent disks to most instances).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Regional persistent disks can be replicated between two zones in a region for higher availability.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Persistent disk snapshots lets the users copy data from existing persistent disk and apply them to new persistent disks.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] This is especially useful for creating backups of the persistent disk data in cases of unexpected failures and zone maintenance events.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A Google Compute Engine instance is a virtual machine running on a Linux or Microsoft Windows configuration.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Users can choose to modify the instances including customizing the hardware, OS, disk, and other configuration options.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A network defines the address range and gateway address of all instances connected to it.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] It defines how instances communicate with each other, with other networks, and with the outside world.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Each instance belongs to a single network and any communication between instances in different networks must be through a public IP address.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A Cloud Platform Console project can contain multiple networks, and each network can have multiple instances attached to it.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A network allows the user to define a gateway IP and the network range for the instances attached to that network.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] By default, every project is provided with a default network with preset configurations and firewall rules.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Users can choose to customize the default network by adding or removing rules, or they can create new networks in that project.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Generally, most users only need one network, although there can be up to five networks per project by default.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A network belongs to only one project, and each instance can only belong to one network.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] All Compute Engine networks use the IPv4 protocol.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Compute Engine currently does not support IPv6.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] However, Google is a major advocate of IPv6 and it is an important future direction.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] When an instance is created, an ephemeral external IP address is automatically assigned to the instance by default.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] This address is attached to the instance for the life of the instance and is released once the instance has been terminated.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] GCE also provides mechanism to reserve and attach static IPs to the VMs.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] An ephemeral IP address can be promoted to a static IP address.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A firewall resource contains one or more rules that permit connections into instances.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Every firewall resource is associated with one and only one network.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] It is not possible to associate one firewall with multiple networks.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] No communication is allowed into an instance unless a firewall resource permits the network traffic, even between instances on the same network.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google Compute Engine offers a routing table to manage how traffic destined for a certain IP range should be routed.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Similar to a physical router in the local area network, all outbound traffic is compared to the routes table and forwarded appropriately if the outbound packet matches any rules in the routes table.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A region refers to a geographic location of Google's infrastructure facility.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Users can choose to deploy their resources in one of the available regions based on their requirement.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] As of June 1, 2014, Google Compute Engine is available in central US region, Western Europe and Asia East region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] A zone is an isolated location within a region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Zones have high-bandwidth, low-latency network connections to other zones in the same region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] In order to deploy fault-tolerant applications that have high availability, Google recommends deploying applications across multiple zones in a region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] This helps protect against unexpected failures of components, up to and including a single zone.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] As of August 5, 2014, there are eight zones - three each in central US region and Asia East region and two zones in Western Europe region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] All resources within GCE belong to the global, regional, or zonal plane.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Global resources are accessible from all the regions and zones.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] For example, images are a global resource so users can launch a VM in any region based on a global image.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] But an address is a regional resource that is available only to the instances launched in one of the zones within the same region.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Instances are launched in a specific zone that requires the zone specification as a part of all requests made to that instance.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Google charges the VMs for a minimum of 10 minutes.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] At the end of 10th minute, instances are charged in 1-minute increments, rounded up to the nearest minute.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Sustained usage based pricing will credit the discounts to the customers based on the monthly utilisation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Users need not pay a commitment fee upfront to get discounts on the regular, on-demand pricing.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Compute Engine VMs boot within 30 seconds which is considered to be 4-10x faster than the competition.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] The persistent disks of Compute Engine deliver higher IOPS consistently.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] With the cost of provisioned IOPS included within the cost of storage, users need not pay separately for the IOPS.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] Images and disk snapshots belong to the global scope which means they are implicitly available across all the regions and zones of Google Cloud Platform.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] This avoids the need for exporting and importing images and snapshots between regions.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] During the scheduled maintenance of Google data center, Compute Engine can automatically migrate the VMs from one host to the other without involving any action from the users.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/google-compute-engine] This delivers better uptime to applications.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] A **hypervisor**, also known as a **virtual machine monitor** (**VMM**), is a type of computer software, firmware or hardware that creates and runs virtual machines.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] A computer on which a hypervisor runs one or more virtual machines is called a *host machine* or *virtualization server*, and each virtual machine is called a *guest machine*.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The hypervisor presents the guest operating systems with a virtual operating platform and manages the execution of the guest operating systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Unlike an emulator, the guest executes most instructions on the native hardware.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Multiple instances of a variety of operating systems may share the virtualized hardware resources: for example, Linux, Windows, and macOS instances can all run on a single physical x86 machine.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] This contrasts with operating system-level virtualization, where all instances (usually called *containers*) must share a single kernel, though the guest operating systems can differ in user space, such as different Linux distributions with the same kernel.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The term *hypervisor* is a variant of *supervisor*, a traditional term for the kernel of an operating system: the hypervisor is the supervisor of the supervisors, with *hyper-* used as a stronger variant of *super-*.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The term dates to circa 1970; IBM coined it for software that ran OS/360 and the 7090 emulator concurrently on the 360/65 and later used it for the DIAG handler of CP-67.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] In the earlier CP/CMS (1967) system, the term *Control Program* was used instead.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Some literature, especially in microkernel contexts, makes a distinction between *hypervisor* and *virtual machine monitor* (*VMM*).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] There, both components form the overall *virtualization stack* of a certain system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] *Hypervisor* refers to kernel-space functionality and VMM to user-space functionality.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Specifically in these contexts, a *hypervisor* is a microkernel implementing virtualization infrastructure that must run in kernel-space for technical reasons, such as Intel VMX.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Microkernels implementing virtualization mechanisms are also referred to as *microhypervisor*.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Applying this terminology to Linux, KVM is a *hypervisor* and QEMU or Cloud Hypervisor are VMMs utilizing KVM as hypervisor.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] In his 1973 thesis *Architectural Principles for Virtual Computer Systems*, Robert P.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] These hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware to control the hardware and to manage guest operating systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The first hypervisors, which IBM developed in the 1960s, were native hypervisors.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] These hypervisors run on a conventional operating system (OS) just as other computer programs do.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Type-2 hypervisors abstract guest operating systems from the host operating system, effectively creating an isolated system that can be interacted with by the host.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The distinction between these two types is not always clear.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] For instance, KVM and bhyve are kernel modules that effectively convert the host operating system to a type-1 hypervisor.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The first hypervisors providing full virtualization were the test tool SIMMON and the one-off IBM CP-40 research system, which began production use in January 1967 and became the first version of the IBM CP/CMS operating system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] CP-40 ran on a S/360-40 modified at the Cambridge Scientific Center to support dynamic address translation, a feature that enabled virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Prior to this time, computer hardware had only been virtualized to the extent to allow multiple user applications to run concurrently, such as in CTSS and IBM M44/44X.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] With CP-40, the hardware's *supervisor state* was virtualized as well, allowing multiple operating systems to run concurrently in separate virtual machine contexts.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Programmers soon implemented CP-40 (as CP-67) for the IBM System/360-67, the first production computer system capable of full virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] IBM shipped this machine in 1966; it included page-translation-table hardware for virtual memory and other techniques that allowed a full virtualization of all kernel tasks, including I/O and interrupt handling.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] (The "official" operating system, the ill-fated TSS/360, did not employ full virtualization.) Both CP-40 and CP-67 began production use in 1967.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] CP/CMS was available to IBM customers from 1968 to early 1970s, in source code form without support.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] CP/CMS formed part of IBM's attempt to build robust time-sharing systems for its mainframe computers.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] By running multiple operating systems concurrently, the hypervisor increased system robustness and stability: Even if one operating system crashed, the others would continue working without interruption.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Indeed, this even allowed beta or experimental versions of operating systems‍—‌or even of new hardware‍—‌to be deployed and debugged, without jeopardizing the stable main production system, and without requiring costly additional development systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] IBM announced its System/370 series in 1970 without the virtual memory feature needed for virtualization, but added it in the August 1972 Advanced Function announcement.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Virtualization has been featured in all successor systems, such that all modern-day IBM mainframes, including the zSeries line, retain backward compatibility with the 1960s-era IBM S/360 line.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The 1972 announcement also included VM/370, a reimplementation of CP/CMS for the S/370.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Unlike CP/CMS, IBM provided support for this version (though it was still distributed in source code form for several releases).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] *VM* stands for *Virtual Machine*, emphasizing that all, not just some, of the hardware interfaces are virtualized.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Both VM and CP/CMS enjoyed early acceptance and rapid development by universities, corporate users, and time-sharing vendors, as well as within IBM.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Users played an active role in ongoing development, anticipating trends seen in modern open source projects.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] However, in a series of disputed and bitter battles, time-sharing lost out to batch processing through IBM political infighting, and VM remained IBM's "other" mainframe operating system for decades, losing to MVS.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] It enjoyed a resurgence of popularity and support from 2000 as the z/VM product, for example as the platform for Linux on IBM Z.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] As mentioned above, the VM control program includes a *hypervisor-call* handler that intercepts DIAG ("Diagnose", opcode x'83') instructions used within a virtual machine.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] This provides fast-path non-virtualized execution of file-system access and other operations (DIAG is a model-dependent privileged instruction, not used in normal programming, and thus is not virtualized.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] It is therefore available for use as a signal to the "host" operating system).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] When first implemented in CP/CMS release 3.1, this use of DIAG provided an operating system interface that was analogous to the System/360 Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), but that did not require altering or extending the system's virtualization of SVC.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] In 1985 IBM introduced the PR/SM hypervisor to manage logical partitions (LPAR).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Major Unix vendors, including HP, IBM, SGI, and Sun Microsystems, have been selling virtualized hardware since before 2000.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] These have generally been large, expensive systems (in the multimillion-dollar range at the high end), although virtualization has also been available on some low- and mid-range systems, such as IBM pSeries servers, HP Superdome series machines, and Sun/Oracle SPARC T series CoolThreads servers.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] IBM provides virtualization partition technology known as logical partitioning (LPAR) on System/390, zSeries, pSeries and IBM AS/400 systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] For IBM's Power Systems, the POWER Hypervisor (PHYP) is a native (bare-metal) hypervisor in firmware and provides isolation between LPARs.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Processor capacity is provided to LPARs in either a dedicated fashion or on an entitlement basis where unused capacity is harvested and can be re-allocated to busy workloads.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Groups of LPARs can have their processor capacity managed as if they were in a "pool" - IBM refers to this capability as Multiple Shared-Processor Pools (MSPPs) and implements it in servers with the POWER6 processor.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] LPAR and MSPP capacity allocations can be dynamically changed.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Memory is allocated to each LPAR (at LPAR initiation or dynamically) and is address-controlled by the POWER Hypervisor.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] For real-mode addressing by operating systems (AIX, Linux, IBM i), the Power processors (POWER4 onwards) have designed virtualization capabilities where a hardware address-offset is evaluated with the OS address-offset to arrive at the physical memory address.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Input/Output (I/O) adapters can be exclusively "owned" by LPARs or shared by LPARs through an appliance partition known as the Virtual I/O Server (VIOS).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] HPE provides HP Integrity Virtual Machines (Integrity VM) to host multiple operating systems on their Itanium powered Integrity systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Itanium can run HP-UX, Linux, Windows and OpenVMS, and these environments are also supported as virtual servers on HP's Integrity VM platform.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] While it heavily leverages HP-UX, the Integrity VM hypervisor is really a hybrid that runs on bare-metal while guests are executing.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Running normal HP-UX applications on an Integrity VM host is heavily discouraged, because Integrity VM implements its own memory management, scheduling and I/O policies that are tuned for virtual machines and are not as effective for normal applications.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] HPE also provides more rigid partitioning of their Integrity and HP9000 systems by way of VPAR and nPar technology, the former offering shared resource partitioning and the latter offering complete I/O and processing isolation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The flexibility of virtual server environment (VSE) has given way to its use more frequently in newer deployments.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Wind River "Carrier Grade Linux" also runs on Sun's Hypervisor.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Full virtualization on SPARC processors proved straightforward: since its inception in the mid-1980s Sun deliberately kept the SPARC architecture clean of artifacts that would have impeded virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Similar trends have occurred with x86/x86-64 server platforms, where open-source projects such as Xen have led virtualization efforts.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] These include hypervisors built on Linux and Solaris kernels as well as custom kernels.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Since these technologies span from large systems down to desktops, they are described in the next section.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] x86 virtualization was introduced in the 1990s, with its emulation being included in Bochs.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Intel and AMD released their first x86 processors with hardware virtualisation in 2005 with Intel VT-x (code-named Vanderpool) and AMD-V (code-named Pacifica).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] An alternative approach requires modifying the guest operating system to make a system call to the underlying hypervisor, rather than executing machine I/O instructions that the hypervisor simulates.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] This is called paravirtualization in Xen, a "hypercall" in Parallels Workstation, and a "DIAGNOSE code" in IBM VM.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Some microkernels, such as Mach and L4, are flexible enough to allow paravirtualization of guest operating systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Embedded hypervisors, targeting embedded systems and certain real-time operating system (RTOS) environments, are designed with different requirements when compared to desktop and enterprise systems, including robustness, security and real-time capabilities.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] The resource-constrained nature of multiple embedded systems, especially battery-powered mobile systems, imposes a further requirement for small memory-size and low overhead.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Finally, in contrast to the ubiquity of the x86 architecture in the PC world, the embedded world uses a wider variety of architectures and less standardized environments.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Support for virtualization requires memory protection (in the form of a memory management unit or at least a memory protection unit) and a distinction between user mode and privileged mode, which rules out most microcontrollers.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] This still leaves x86, MIPS, ARM and PowerPC as widely deployed architectures on medium- to high-end embedded systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] As manufacturers of embedded systems usually have the source code to their operating systems, they have less need for full virtualization in this space.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Instead, the performance advantages of paravirtualization make this usually the virtualization technology of choice.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Nevertheless, ARM and MIPS have recently added full virtualization support as an IP option and has included it in their latest high-end processors and architecture versions, such as ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore and ARMv8 EL2.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] Implementation of the concept has allegedly occurred in the SubVirt laboratory rootkit (developed jointly by Microsoft and University of Michigan researchers) as well as in the Blue Pill malware package.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] However, such assertions have been disputed by others who claim that it would be possible to detect the presence of a hypervisor-based rootkit.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/hypervisor] In 2009, researchers from Microsoft and North Carolina State University demonstrated a hypervisor-layer anti-rootkit called Hooksafe that can provide generic protection against kernel-mode rootkits.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS-cloud providers supply resources on-demand from the large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks, VPNs).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] To deploy their applications, users install operating-system images and the application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] Users patch and maintain the operating systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS services are typically billed as a utility: cost reflects the amount of resources allocated or consumed.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] Typically, IaaS involves the use of a cloud orchestration technology such as OpenStack, Apache CloudStack, or OpenNebula.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] It manages the creation of a virtual machine (VM) and decides on the hypervisor (i.e. physical host) in order to start it.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] A hypervisor runs virtual machines (VMs) as guests.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] Pools of hypervisors in the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to demand by customers.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] Hypervisors include Xen, Oracle VirtualBox, Oracle VM, KVM, VMware ESX/ESXi, or Microsoft Hyper-V.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] It also enables VM migration between hosts, allocates storage volumes, and attaches them to VMs that track usage information for billing.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] An alternative to hypervisors is Linux containers, which run in isolated partitions of a Linux kernel that runs directly on the physical hardware.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containers are isolated, secured and managed using Linux cgroups and namespaces.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containerisation offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] The global IaaS market is projected to reach a value of $411.9 billion by 2030, expanding at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 22.6% from 2023 to 2030.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] This growth is primarily driven by the adoption of cloud-based infrastructure within the Banking, Financial Services, and Insurance (BFSI) sector, which employs these technologies to enhance scalability and reduce operational costs.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to use public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS is in use within the UK Government but the technology community within government recommends consideration of Platform as a Service (PaaS) in cases where a department may not have IaaS skills and management capacity.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Live migration requires the entire VM's state to be transferred from the source host to the target host.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] This state includes the state of any components of the VM, for example, the register contents of the virtual CPUs (vCPUs).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] The state of the VM is not stable until the VM is paused.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] For example, until the vCPUs have been paused, the state in the virtual registers may be changing.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] The simplest way to implement live migration is to pause the VM, serialize and send the state to the target host, and resume the VM on the target host.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Serializing and sending certain state, like the state of the VM's main memory or locally-attached storage devices, can be slow.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] If the entire contents of the VM's main memory must be copied while the VM is paused, the VM will have to remain paused for an extended period of time, depending on the size of the VM's main memory.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] There are several techniques for reducing blackout for large-memory VMs.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Pre-copy memory migration requires the hypervisor to track which pages the guest is writing to.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Before copying any particular page, track any subsequent writes to the page (e.g. by write-protecting the corresponding SLAT entry).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] After all pages have been copied, start a new copying pass, but only copy pages that were written to since it was last copied to the target host (i.e., pages that are "dirty").
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Repeat step 3 until the set of remaining dirty pages is small.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Pause the VM, and transfer the remaining dirty pages to the target host.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Other optimizations can be applied, like not re-sending pages that will likely be dirtied again quickly.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] The guest is usually able to write to memory faster than it can be copied to the target, which means that pre-copy might never converge to a small dirty set.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] If the hypervisor does not throttle writes to guest memory, blackout time may remain large, even with pre-copy memory migration.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Post-copy memory migration is a strategy for transferring a VM's main memory outside of blackout.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] It can complement pre-copy by reducing pause time when pre-copy does not converge on a small set of dirty pages.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] It requires the hypervisor to intercept guest memory accesses, allowing the VM to resume on the target host without a complete memory copy.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Accesses to pages not yet present on the target (e.g., pages dirtied during pre-copy) are fetched on demand by the hypervisor.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] To ensure that all dirty pages are eventually transferred, a hypervisor implementing post-copy live migration will also fetch outstanding dirty pages in the background, concurrently with on-demand fetching of dirty pages.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] Post-copy transfers each page only once, whereas pre-copy may resend pages multiple times if they are repeatedly modified.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] However, pre-copy maintains a consistent VM state on the source, while post-copy splits state between source and destination.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/live-migration] As a result, failures during post-copy cannot be recovered, unlike pre-copy, which can be restarted.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:gcp-compute-engine/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
